@Node "HISTORY" "History"
@{jcenter}
@{fg highlight}@{b}Stages of program creation@{fg text}@{bg back}
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
@{ub}
@{jleft}@{lindent 1}
version 0.76 beta @{fg highlight}(10.11.97)@{fg text}@{lindent 12}
- First official beta version for testing.@{lindent 1}
version 0.84 beta @{fg highlight}(14.12.97)@{fg text}@{lindent 12}
- Next official beta version for testing.
- Improved output format for all separator parameter strings. Now the program reports "SPACE" not only for standard space code but also for any whitespace code.
- Fixed incorrect recognition of the currency symbol position for positive/negative monetary values (per a report of Francis Labrie).@{lindent 1}
version 0.86 beta @{fg highlight}(17.12.97)@{fg text}@{lindent 12}
- Next official beta version for testing.
- Improved output format for Country Code string. In fact, the number was shown correctly, but the abbreviation was wrong, omitting the last letter. Now fixed.
- Improved the function which checks the results of letter transformation. The function didn't support multi-symbol conversion. For example, some Russian letters must be transformed into not one Latin sign but into several. Now it works correctly.@{lindent 1}
version 1.0 @{fg highlight}(20.12.97)@{fg text}@{lindent 12}
- The first public version.@{lindent 1}
version 2.0 @{fg highlight}(1.1.99)@{fg text}@{lindent 12}
- Improved procedure for freeing resources (main bug).
- Changed program graphics.
- Full resizable intarface.
- Shows national flag of country.
- Supports many languages. Thanks to @{" AŃÍ " Link "ATO"}!@{lindent 1}
version 2.1 @{fg highlight}(7.1.99)@{fg text}@{lindent 12}
- The second public Aminet realization.
- Added tooltype "NLIST". If you have installed NList MUI custom class but don't wish to use it in the program then use value NLIST=NO or NLIST=FALSE.
@EndNode
@Node "DSC" "Description"
@{jcenter}
@{fg highlight}@{b}Description and scope of employment@{fg text}@{bg back}
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
@{ub}
@{jleft}@{lindent 1}    Much time has passed since the first attempt was made to teach a computer to interact with the user in his native language. In 1991 Commodore made the greatest step in this regard, as it had elaborated and realized the concept of system localization for "Amiga" computers.

   Localization is the process by which software dynamically adapts to different locales. This process takes into consideration numerous attributes, such as: country name, language, measuring system, rules for printing numbers, date, monetary values, punctuation signs, some rules for correct word sorting, letter conversion etc, and such additional data as: time zone, telephone area codes, common words and phrases...

   The basis of the Localization System is a shared library called locale.library. In one system control is executed for the main entries of localization: data base of country and language, language catalogs and conversion, and other functions.

   Most localization data and rules are placed in two files: language file (for example, russian.language) and country (russia.country).

   But after Commodore went bankrupt never did any of subsequent Amiga owners emphasize improvement of localization software. As a result, by 1993 only about ten language drivers were created and officially published. At the same time Amiga continued to spread to new countries, and the localization process became unmanaged. In fact, for some languages there are two or more different language files. More and more often these files contain many errors.

   The program @{b}LocaleTest@{ub} is mainly for programmers who try to create language drivers and country locale files (*.country and *.language). With this software you will be able to check your own work, because @{b}LocaleTest@{ub} checks for both these files and outputs in a clear and easy form. None the less any Amiga user may use it if he needs to check whether it works correctly for his localization system.

   The following list contains the main localization entries which are checked by @{b}LocaleTest@{ub}:

@{apen 2}General@{fg text}@{lindent 8}
- name of localization preferences file;
- language name;
- country name;
- international country code;
- country dialling code;
- measuring system;
- number of code table;
- some localization flags;
- predefined languages names;@{lindent 1}
@{apen 2}Numbering@{fg text}@{lindent 8}
- decimal point;
- @{lindent 10}algorithm for grouping before and after decimal point;@{lindent 1}
@{apen 2}Monetary@{fg text}@{lindent 8}
- large and small currency symbols;
- international currency symbol (ISO-4217);
- decimal point for currency values;
- @{lindent 10}algorithm for grouping before and after decimal point for currency values;@{lindent 8}
- spaces in currency values;
- @{lindent 10}positive and negative signs for currency values;@{lindent 8}
- @{lindent 10}currency string layout for currency symbol, value, sing and spaces for ones;@{lindent 1}
@{apen 2}Database of words@{fg text}@{lindent 8}
- affirmative and negative responses;
- hupernation signs and quotation marks;@{lindent 1}
@{apen 2}Date and time@{fg text}@{lindent 8}
- time zone;
- first day of week;
- names of time periods;
- names and abbreviations of days and months;
- full and short formats for outputting date and time;@{lindent 1}
@{apen 2}Alphabet@{fg text}@{lindent 8}
- sorting and conversion letters by all locale rules;
- 11 flags of letters.
@{lindent 1}

All these and some other localization entries are described in corresponding chapters.
@EndNode
@Node "INSTALL" "Installation"
@{jcenter}
@{fg highlight}@{b}Program installation@{fg text}@{bg back}
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
@{ub}
@{jleft}@{lindent 1}    There is not hard-to-install software. Create a new directory and copy to it all files and directories from the distribution archive.

   For further use of this procedure read the chapter @{" use " Link "USG"} program.
@EndNode
@Node "USG" "Usage"
@{jcenter}
@{fg highlight}@{b}Program usage@{fg text}@{bg back}
~~~~~~~~~~~~~
@{ub}
@{jleft}@{lindent 1}    Before use the program must be @{" installed " Link "INSTALL"}.

   It is not hard to use @{b}LocaleTest@{ub}. First, note that the program has a Hot Help System. To call it up, simply put the cursor on the desired object and press the @{b}HELP@{ub} key.

   After the program is run you may select a desired part to test with @{" ListView " Link "MLS"} which is plased in the left side of the program window. The results of tests are shown in the right side of window. As a rule, the results are two listviews. One is for checking data, the other for examples. You may change the width of these lists using the @{" Ballance Regulator " Link "BLS"} which is between the listviews.

   Additionally there are some @{" Icon Buttons " Link "PIC"} under ListView. Try them out!

   All these gadgets are described in their corresponding chapters.

   Control of the program interface may be performed by either mouse or keyboard. For keyboard control select any gadget by pressing the TAB key one or more times. Then use the special control keys (as a rule, they are the cursor keys, Enter, and Space).
@EndNode
@Node "BLS" "Ballance Regulator"
@{jcenter}
@{fg highlight}@{b}The change of listviews' width@{fg text}@{bg back}
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
@{ub}
@{jleft}@{lindent 1}    The contents of parameters listview and of the example listview may be very different from test to test. If the width of any listview is small for you view the string at full lenght, then simply alter the width of listview. There is a vertical bar between listviews for this. Select one and move it left or right to the desired position.
@EndNode
@Node "PIC" "Icon Buttons"
@{jcenter}
@{fg highlight}@{b}Usage of buttons with images@{fg text}@{bg back}
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
@{ub}
@{jleft}@{lindent 1}    These buttons give the user additional capabilities, such us:

- Getting information about the version of program;
- Popup Help Guide;
- Calling the Locale Preferences program;
- Running the @{" MUI " Link "MUI"} configuration program.
@EndNode
@Node "MLS" "ListView"
@{jcenter}
@{fg highlight}@{b}Selection of objects for testing@{fg text}@{bg back}
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
@{ub}
@{jleft}@{lindent 1}    With the ListView you can select the part of Localization System to be tested. At present there are the following sections:
@{settabs 34}@{lindent 8}
@{" General              " Link "GPG"}
@{" Numbering            " Link "SPG"}
@{" Monetary             " Link "MPG"}
@{" Letters              " Link "CPG"}
@{" Strings              " Link "IPG"}
@{" Date and Time        " Link "DPG"}
@EndNode
@Node "GPG" "General"
@{jcenter}
@{fg highlight}@{b}General information about country and language@{fg text}@{bg back}
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
@{ub}
@{jleft}@{lindent 1}    This part shows some general information about country and language of the user. This information is shown in two listviews.

   The left listview contains some parameters and their values, such us:

@{apen 2}Locale's Name@{fg text}@{lindent 8}
The name of the file which contains localization preferences.@{lindent 1}
@{apen 2}Language@{fg text}@{lindent 8}
Name of user's main language.@{lindent 1}
@{apen 2}Country@{fg text}@{lindent 8}
Name of country in which the user lives.@{lindent 1}
@{apen 2}Country Code@{fg text}@{lindent 8}
International country code. It is an abbreviation (1-3 letters) defined by ISO standard.@{lindent 1}
@{apen 2}Telephone Code@{fg text}@{lindent 8}
Number prefix for selected country if an international call.@{lindent 1}
@{apen 2}Measuring@{fg text}@{lindent 8}
Measuring system in user's country. There are four types:
- International (defined by ISO standard);
- Amirican;
- Imperial;
- British.@{lindent 1}
@{apen 2}Locale Flags@{fg text}@{lindent 8}
Not defined. Currently must be zero.@{lindent 1}
@{apen 2}CodeSet table@{fg text}@{lindent 8}
Not defined. Currently must be zero.@{lindent 1}

   Right listview contains the names of user-defined languages in priority order. This listview shows which languages the Localization System may try to interact with the user. For example, if the program opens a catalog of messages then the Localization System first of all tries to use the top language on this list. If that catalog is absent then it will try the next language from list, etc.
@EndNode
@Node "SPG" "Numbering"
@{jcenter}
@{fg highlight}@{b}Information about numbering system@{fg text}@{bg back}
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
@{ub}
@{jleft}@{lindent 1}    This part shows rules for writing non-monetary values.

   The left listview contains some parameters and its values, such us:

@{apen 2}Decimal Point@{fg text}@{lindent 8}
The decimal point character used to format non-monetary quantities.@{lindent 1}
@{apen 2}Before Separator@{fg text}@{lindent 8}
The characters used to separate groups of digits before the decimal-point character in formatted non-monetary quantities.@{lindent 1}
@{apen 2}After Separator@{fg text}@{lindent 8}
The characters used to separate groups of digits after the decimal-point character in formatted non-monetary quantities.@{lindent 1}
@{apen 2}Before Grouping@{fg text}@{lindent 8}
A string whose elements indicate the size of each group of digits before the decimal-point character in formatted non-monetary quantities. Also it may show two special values in the end of string: @{b}PERIOD@{ub} - the previous element is to be repeatedly used for the remainder of the digits; and @{b}NO MORE@{ub} - no further grouping is to be performed.@{lindent 1}
@{apen 2}After Separator@{fg text}@{lindent 8}
The characters used to separate groups of digits after the decimal-point character in formatted non-monetary quantities. Also it may show two special values in the end of string: @{b}PERIOD@{ub} - the previous element is to be repeatedly used for the remainder of the digits; and @{b}NO MORE@{ub} - no further grouping is to be performed.@{lindent 1}

   The right listview shows some examples which use the rules described.
@EndNode
@Node "MPG" "Monetary"
@{jcenter}
@{fg highlight}@{b}Information about monetary system@{fg text}@{bg back}
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
@{ub}
@{jleft}@{lindent 1}    This part shows rules for printing monetary values and strings.

   The left listview contains some parameters and its values, such us:

@{apen 2}Currency Symbol@{fg text}@{lindent 8}
The local currency symbol applicable to the current locale.@{lindent 1}
@{apen 2}Small Currency Symbol@{fg text}@{lindent 8}
The currency symbol for small amounts.@{lindent 1}
@{apen 2}International Currency Symbol@{fg text}@{lindent 8}
The international currency symbol applicable to the current locale. These characters contain the alphabetic international currency symbol in accordance with those specified in ISO 4217 Codes for the Representation of Currency and Funds.@{lindent 1}
@{apen 2}International Symbol Separator@{fg text}@{lindent 8}
The character used to separate the international currency symbol from the monetary quantity.@{lindent 1}
@{apen 2}Decimal Point@{fg text}@{lindent 8}
The decimal-point used to format monetary quantities.@{lindent 1}
@{apen 2}Before Separator@{fg text}@{lindent 8}
The separator for groups of digits before the decimal-point in monetary quantities.@{lindent 1}
@{apen 2}After Separator@{fg text}@{lindent 8}
The separator for groups of digits after the decimal-point in monetary quantities.@{lindent 1}
@{apen 2}Before Grouping@{fg text}@{lindent 8}
A string whose elements indicate the size of each group of digits before the decimal-point character in monetary quantities. Also it may show two special values in the end of string: @{b}PERIOD@{ub} - the previous element is to be repeatedly used for the remainder of the digits; and @{b}NO MORE@{ub} - no further grouping is to be performed.@{lindent 1}
@{apen 2}After Grouping@{fg text}@{lindent 8}
A string whose elements indicate the size of each group of digits after the decimal-point character in monetary quantities. Also it may show two special values in the end of string: @{b}PERIOD@{ub} - the previous element is to be repeatedly used for the remainder of the digits; and @{b}NO MORE@{ub} - no further grouping is to be performed.@{lindent 1}
@{apen 2}Fractional Digits@{fg text}@{lindent 8}
The number of fractional digits (those after the decimal-point) to be displayed in a formatted monetary quantity.@{lindent 1}
@{apen 2}International Fractional Digits@{fg text}@{lindent 8}
The number of fractional digits (those after the decimal-point) to be displayed in an internationally formatted monetary quantity.@{lindent 1}
@{apen 2}Sign@{fg text}@{lindent 8}
The string used to indicate a (non-)negative monetary quantity.@{lindent 1}
@{apen 2}Number Spaces@{fg text}@{lindent 8}
Specifies the number of spaces separating the currency symbol from monetary quantity.@{lindent 1}
@{apen 2}Sign Position@{fg text}@{lindent 8}
Set to a value indicating the positioning of the Sign for monetary quantity. It may be:
- parentheses surround the quantity and currency symbol;
- the sign string precedes the quantity and currency symbol;
- the sign string succeeds the quantity and currency symbol;
- the sign string immediately precedes the currency symbol;
- The sign string immediately succeeds the currency symbol.@{lindent 1}
@{apen 2}Symbol Position@{fg text}@{lindent 8}
Define do Currency Symbol precedes or succeeds the value for monetary quantity.@{lindent 1}

   The right listview shows some examples which use the rules described.
@EndNode
@Node "CPG" "Letters"
@{jcenter}
@{fg highlight}@{b}Information about letters@{fg text}@{bg back}
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
@{ub}
@{jleft}@{lindent 1}    This part shows information about all letters for the current language. This data is a result of functions from locale.library. Information is shown in @{" Letters List " Link "CLT"} and additionally may be checked for some parameters by gadgets @{" Flags " Link "CFL"}.
@EndNode
@Node "CLT" "Letters: List"
@{jcenter}
@{fg highlight}@{b}Information about letters@{fg text}@{bg back}
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
@{ub}
@{jleft}@{lindent 1}    This part shows information about all letters for the current language. This data is a result of functions from locale.library. Information is shown in letters list and additionally may be checked for some parameters by gadgets @{" Flags " Link "CFL"}.

   The letters list contains all values for the character table. The list has some columns, such us:

@{apen 2}Sign@{fg text}@{lindent 8}
Alphabet, numbering or any other character which can be printed in graphic form. If not, then the hexadecimal value will be printed instead.@{lindent 1}
@{apen 2}Graphics@{fg text}@{lindent 8}
Flag: is it a visible character?@{lindent 1}
@{apen 2}Printable@{fg text}@{lindent 8}
Flag: is it a printable character?@{lindent 1}
@{apen 2}Alphabet@{fg text}@{lindent 8}
Flag: is it an alphabetical character?@{lindent 1}
@{apen 2}AlphaNumeric@{fg text}@{lindent 8}
Flag: is it an alphabet or numeric character?@{lindent 1}
@{apen 2}Control@{fg text}@{lindent 8}
Flag: is it a control character?@{lindent 1}
@{apen 2}Space@{fg text}@{lindent 8}
Flag: is it a white space character?@{lindent 1}
@{apen 2}Punctuation@{fg text}@{lindent 8}
Flag: is it punctuation character?@{lindent 1}
@{apen 2}Upper@{fg text}@{lindent 8}
There are two values in this column. First, there is a flag: is it a capital letter? Secondly, if the character is lower case, then this column contains the same letter in upper case.@{lindent 1}
@{apen 2}Lower@{fg text}@{lindent 8}
There are two values in this column. First, there is a flag: is it small letter? Secondly, if the character is upper case, then this column contains the same letter in lower case.@{lindent 1}
@{apen 2}Digit@{fg text}@{lindent 8}
Flag: is it a decimal digit character?@{lindent 1}
@{apen 2}HexDigit@{fg text}@{lindent 8}
Flag: is it hexadecimal digit?@{lindent 1}
@{apen 2}Conversion@{fg text}@{lindent 8}
This column contains the result of the conversion function from locale.library.@{lindent 1}
@EndNode
@Node "CFL" "Letters: Flags"
@{jcenter}
@{fg highlight}@{b}Information about letters@{fg text}@{bg back}
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
@{ub}
@{jleft}@{lindent 1}    This part shows information about all letters for the current language. This data is a result of functions from locale.library. Information is shown in @{" Letters List " Link "CLT"} and additionally may be checked for some parameters by the Flags gadgets.

   There are two gadgets: sorting flags and conversion flags.
@{jcenter}
@{u}Sorting@{uu}
@{jleft}@{lindent 1}
This flag defines rules for sorting of @{" Letters List " Link "CLT"}. The compare and sorting functions from locale.library permits use of the following methods:

@{apen 2}By number@{fg text}@{lindent 8}
No functions used. All entries are placed by character code.@{lindent 1}
@{apen 2}ASCII mode@{fg text}@{lindent 8}
It causes an ASCII-based case-insensitive comparison to be performed. The ASCII method is the fastest of the comparison types, but it uses ASCII ordering and considers accented characters differently from their non-accented counterparts.@{lindent 1}
@{apen 2}Collate 1@{fg text}@{lindent 8}
It causes the characters to be compared using their primary sorting order. This effectively produces a comparison that ignores letter case and diacritical marks.@{lindent 1}
@{apen 2}Collate 2@{fg text}@{lindent 8}
It causes the characters to be compared using both their primary and secondary sorting order. It is slower than Collate 1. This is the type of comparison to use when sorting data to be presented to the user. It operates in two passes. First it performs a comparison equivalent to Collate 1. If both strings match, then a second pass is made using the secondary sorting order, which gives finer resolution to the comparison.@{lindent 1}

@{jcenter}
@{u}Conversion@{uu}
@{jleft}@{lindent 1}
   This flag defines rules for conversion entries in @{" Letters List " Link "CLT"} from the left column to right one. Conversion function from locale.library allow methods: @{b}ASCII@{ub}, @{b}Collate 1@{ub} and @{b}Collate 2@{ub}. These methods are same as ones of compare function (see above).


@{i}Note@{ui}: If any change is made for the value of these two flags then an update process of @{" Letters List " Link "CLT"}. will be run.
@EndNode
@Node "IPG" "Strings"
@{jcenter}
@{fg highlight}@{b}Information about built-in strings@{fg text}@{bg back}
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
@{ub}
@{jleft}@{lindent 1}    This part shows information about strings which are built into Localization System. This information is shown in two listviews.

   The left listview contains some strings which are used for date output, such us:

- 7 complete names and 7 abbreviations for days of week;
- 12 complete names and 12 abbreviations for months.


   The right listview contants some other strings, such us:

- affirmative and negative response for yes/no queries;
- variants of "before noon" and "after noon" periods;
- variants of words Yesterday, Today, Tomorrow and Future;
- signs for the dash and hyphen;
- signs for start and end of quoted block.
@EndNode
@Node "DPG" "Date&Time"
@{jcenter}
@{fg highlight}@{b}Information about date and time@{fg text}@{bg back}
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
@{ub}
@{jleft}@{lindent 1}    This part shows information about the format for outputting date and time in the user's country and some other information.

   The left listview contains some strings, which are used for date output, such us:

@{apen 2}Time Zone@{fg text}@{lindent 8}
The time difference of the current location from GMT.@{lindent 1}
@{apen 2}First Day@{fg text}@{lindent 8}
The name of first day in the week.@{lindent 1}
@{apen 2}DateTime@{fg text}@{lindent 8}
The date and time format string.@{lindent 1}
@{apen 2}Date@{fg text}@{lindent 8}
The date format string.@{lindent 1}
@{apen 2}Time@{fg text}@{lindent 8}
The time format string.@{lindent 1}


   The right listview shows some examples which use rules described.
@EndNode
